into two parts using Bayes’ rule as follows:\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | P​(W|𝐗)=P​(W)​P​(𝐗|W)P​(𝐗).P({W}|\\mathbf{X})=\\frac{P({W})P(\\mathbf{X}|{W})}{P(\\mathbf{X})}~.italic\\_P ( italic\\_W | bold\\_X ) = divide start\\_ARG italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) italic\\_P ( bold\\_X | italic\\_W ) end\\_ARG start\\_ARG italic\\_P ( bold\\_X ) end\\_ARG . |  | (2) |\n\nSince the probability of P​(𝐗)P(\\mathbf{X})italic\\_P ( bold\\_X ) does not change the optimal word sequence we can write ([2](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S3.E2 \"In III Background ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\")) as\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | W∗=arg⁡maxW⁡P​(𝐗|W)​P​(W),{W}^{\\*}=\\arg\\max\\_{{W}}P(\\mathbf{X}|{W})P({W})~,italic\\_W start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = roman\\_arg roman\\_max start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_W end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_P ( bold\\_X | italic\\_W ) italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) , |  | (3) |\n\nwhere P​(𝐗|W)P(\\mathbf{X}|{W})italic\\_P ( bold\\_X | italic\\_W ) represents the probability of the audio sequence given the word sequence, and it is referred to as the *acoustic model*, and the probability P​(W)P({W})italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) represents the probability of the word sequence and is called *language model*. The process of identifying the word sequence W∗{W}^{\\*}italic\\_W start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT that maximizes the MAP estimate is known as *decoding*. We provide a brief overview of each component, focusing on aspects pertinent to our proposed approach.\n\n### III-A Acoustic model\n\nTraditionally, the acoustic model P​(𝐗|W)P(\\mathbf{X}|{W})italic\\_P ( bold\\_X | italic\\_W ) was estimated using HMMs. In its standard form, an individual HMM is defined for each phone, and word-level HMMs are constructed by sequentially concatenating the phone-specific models. To represent an entire utterance, the HMMs corresponding to each word in the sequence W{W}italic\\_W are further concatenated, yielding a single HMM that models the full spoken input [[33](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib33)]. The model presumes that the probability of transitioning to a particular state depends solely on the current state, independent of the previous states. Additionally, the output probability of a speech frame is considered conditionally independent of prior or future frames, given the current state [[32](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib32)]. HMM-based acoustic models lag behind modern transformer-based models.\n\nOur work focuses on modern recent acoustic models, based on self-supervised learning representations, such as wav2vec 2.0 [[9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9)] and HuBERT [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib10)]. These models are initially trained on raw, unlabeled audio to learn contextualized representations of speech. Then, they are fine-tuned on transcribed speech data using the Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) loss function [[5](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib5)], enabling them to serve as effective acoustic models for automatic speech recognition. This loss enables them to operate directly on character sequences, rather than phonetic states, without requiring explicit alignment between the input audio and target output. As a result, these models adopt a fundamentally different formulation of the acoustic modeling task. Instead of estimating P​(𝐗|W)P(\\mathbf{X}|{W})italic\\_P ( bold\\_X | italic\\_W ), they estimate the posterior probabilities P​(Y|𝐗)P({Y}|\\mathbf{X})italic\\_P ( italic\\_Y | bold\\_X ), where Y{Y}italic\\_Y represents a sequence of UUitalic\\_U characters, including the blank token ϵ\\epsilonitalic\\_ϵ. Specifically, Y=(y1,…,yU){Y}=(y\\_{1},\\ldots,y\\_{U})italic\\_Y = ( italic\\_y start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , … , italic\\_y start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_U end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ), with yi∈{a,…,z,ϵ}y\\_{i}\\in\\{a,\\ldots,z,\\epsilon\\}italic\\_y start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∈ { italic\\_a , … , italic\\_z , italic\\_ϵ } [[9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9), [10](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib10)].\n\nWe note that the primary focus of this work is to propose a mechanism for integrating an LLM as the language model component alongside a given acoustic model. As such, we do not address fully end-to-end supervised transformer-based ASR systems, such as Whisper [[34](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib34)], which do not readily separate into distinct acoustic and language modeling components. We leave the exploration of such models for future work.\n\n### III-B Language model\n\nThe language model (LM) plays a critical role in ensuring that the recognized text is linguistically plausible and contextually coherent. Its primary goal is to assign a probability to a given sequence of words and guide the decoding process toward the most likely interpretation of the spoken input. The language model probability P​(W)P({W})italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) is often decomposed as\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | P​(W)=∏n=1NP​(wn|w1n−1),P({W})=\\prod\\_{n=1}^{N}P(w\\_{n}|w\\_{1}^{n-1})~,italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) = ∏ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n = 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_P ( italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT | italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) , |  | (4) |\n\nwhere w1n−1=(w1,…,wn−1)w\\_{1}^{n-1}=(w\\_{1},\\ldots,w\\_{n-1})italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = ( italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , … , italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ). The most commonly used language model in ASR is the N-gram language model [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib10), [9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9)]. This probabilistic model estimates the likelihood of a word sequence by assuming that each word depends only on the preceding N-1 words [[11](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib11)]. A key limitation of N-gram models is their inability to capture long-range dependencies due to their fixed-size context window. More recent approaches employ advanced neural language models, such as Gated Convolutional Neural Networks (GCNNs) [[12](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib12)], a non-recurrent architecture that uses stacked convolutions and a simplified gating mechanism to efficiently model long-range dependencies, and TransformerLM [[13](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib13)], which is based on a decoder-only transformer architecture.\n\nLLMs, such as GPT-2 [[14](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib14)] and LLaMA 2 [[15](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib15)], are deep neural networks based on the transformer architecture, trained to predict the next token (typically a sub-word unit) given a sequence of preceding tokens. Although LLMs follow the same conditional formulation as in ([4](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S3.E4 \"In III-B Language model ‣ III Background ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\")), they differ fundamentally from N-gram models. LLMs are trained using the cross-entropy loss over massive text corpora to learn the parameters of a transformer-based architecture. This training often results in a high norm of the output logit weights, which causes the softmax function to produce an overly sharp, overconfident probability distribution [[35](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib35)].\n\nThe effective use of LLMs as a language model for ASR is still an open problem. While LLM models predict the probability of the next token given the sequence of previous tokens, the resulting probability is not calibrated due to the way they are trained [[36](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib36)]. Furthermore, ASR systems require language models that support incremental scoring, meaning they can evaluate partial word sequences (prefixes), manage multiple parallel hypotheses during beam search, and synchronize closely with the acoustic model’s step-by-step output [[32](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib32)]. However, LLMs are built to process complete sequences in a forward-only manner, making them ill-suited for this role. They lack native support for prefix scoring, cannot easily backtrack or compare multiple evolving hypotheses, and perform best when given the entire context, which is often unavailable in real-time ASR decoding. Since LLMs cannot be directly integrated into the acoustic model, we propose to incorporate them through the decoding process.\n\n### III-C Decoding\n\nThe decoding mechanism refers to the process of inferring the most probable sequence of words (or subwords) given an input speech signal. It combines the outputs of the acoustic model and the language model to generate the final transcription using an efficient search algorithm, such as beam search, stack decoding, or fast match [[37](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib37)].\n\nDecoding in traditional HMM-based systems is done to incrementally find the word sequence that maximizes the practical scoring formula:\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | ScoreHMM​(𝐗,W)=log⁡P​(𝐗|W)+α​log⁡P​(W)+β​|W|,\\text{Score}\\_{\\text{HMM}}(\\mathbf{X},{W})=\\log P(\\mathbf{X}|{W})+\\alpha\\log P({W})+\\beta|{W}|~,Score start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT HMM end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_X , italic\\_W ) = roman\\_log italic\\_P ( bold\\_X | italic\\_W ) + italic\\_α roman\\_log italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) + italic\\_β | italic\\_W | , |  | (5) |\n\nwhere α\\alphaitalic\\_α scales the influence of the language model, β\\betaitalic\\_β is the *word insertion penalty* that penalizes (or rewards) the number of words to avoid overgeneration or undergeneration, and |W||{W}|| italic\\_W | is the number of words in the hypothesis. This formulation allows a beam search or Viterbi decoder to efficiently explore the space of possible word sequences (as expressed by the HMM states) and choose the one with the highest combined score [[33](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib33)].\n\nIn contrast to HMMs, acoustic models that are based on wav2vec 2.0 [[9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9)] and HuBERT [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib10)] are trained using the CTC loss function [[5](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib5)] on characters. During decoding of these models, a prefix beam search decoding is used, and the scoring function for each candidate word sequence W{W}italic\\_W is formulated as\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | ScoreCTC​(𝐗,W)=log⁡PCTC​(W|𝐗)+α​log⁡P​(W)+β​|W|,\\text{Score}\\_{\\text{CTC}}(\\mathbf{X},{W})=\\log P\\_{\\text{CTC}}({W}|\\mathbf{X})+\\alpha\\log P({W})+\\beta|{W}|~,Score start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT CTC end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_X , italic\\_W ) = roman\\_log italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT CTC end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic\\_W | bold\\_X ) + italic\\_α roman\\_log italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) + italic\\_β | italic\\_W | , |  | (6) |\n\nwhere we assumed that the posterior probability over the characters P​(Y|X)P(Y|X)italic\\_P ( italic\\_Y | italic\\_X ) can be easily translated into a probability over words PCTC​(W|𝐗)P\\_{\\text{CTC}}({W}|\\mathbf{X})italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT CTC end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic\\_W | bold\\_X ). Note that systems based on these acoustic models incorporate language models by multiplying the acoustic model PCTC​(W|𝐗)P\\_{\\text{CTC}}({W}|\\mathbf{X})italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT CTC end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic\\_W | bold\\_X ) by P​(W)P({W})italic\\_P ( italic\\_W ) [[38](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib38), [9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9)]. While this approach yields high performance, it is implausible as it undermines the probabilistic meaning of the models.\n\n## IV Proposed Approach\n\nWe propose integrating the LLM directly into the decoding process. This iterative approach involves sampling multiple tokens from the LLM at each step and aligning each token with the acoustic model to generate a corresponding acoustic score. As we will explain next, this process employs efficient dynamic programming.\n\nFrom this point onward, we will use tokens instead of words; thus, wn∈𝒱w\\_{n}\\in\\mathcal{V}italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∈ caligraphic\\_V denotes a token from the set of all tokens 𝒱\\mathcal{V}caligraphic\\_V. Define the alignment sequence A=(a1,…,aN)A=(a\\_{1},\\ldots,a\\_{N})italic\\_A = ( italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , … , italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ), where an∈[0,T−1]a\\_{n}\\in[0,T-1]italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∈ [ 0 , italic\\_T - 1 ] represents the start time of token wnw\\_{n}italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT for 1≤n≤N1\\leq n\\leq N1 ≤ italic\\_n ≤ italic\\_N. We denote by 𝒜​(W)\\mathcal{A}({W})caligraphic\\_A ( italic\\_W ) the set of all possible alignments (i.e., start times) corresponding to a given token sequence W{W}italic\\_W. Lastly, denote by a1n=(a1,…,an)a\\_{1}^{n}=(a\\_{1},\\ldots,a\\_{n})italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = ( italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , … , italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) the alignment of the first nnitalic\\_n tokens, w1n=(w1,…,wN)w\\_{1}^{n}=(w\\_{1},\\ldots,w\\_{N})italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = ( italic\\_w start\\_POST