IPT LLM end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_X , italic\\_W ) = ∑ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n = 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman\\_log italic\\_P ( italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT | italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , bold\\_X ) |  |\n|  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  |  | +α​∑n=1Nlog⁡P​(wn|w1n−1,a1n−1,𝐗)+β​L​(w1N).\\displaystyle~~~~+\\alpha\\,\\sum\\_{n=1}^{N}\\log P(w\\_{n}|w\\_{1}^{n-1},a\\_{1}^{n-1},\\mathbf{X})+\\beta\\,L(w\\_{1}^{N})~.+ italic\\_α ∑ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n = 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman\\_log italic\\_P ( italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT | italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , bold\\_X ) + italic\\_β italic\\_L ( italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) . |  | (12) |\n\nWe conclude this section by summarizing the proposed method in the form of pseudocode, presented in Algorithm [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#alg1 \"Algorithm 1 ‣ V Algorithmic Implementation ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\"). The algorithm takes as input a speech signal 𝐗\\mathbf{X}bold\\_X, an acoustic model (wav2vec 2.0 [[9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9)] or HuBERT [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib10)]) denoted as AM, and a large language model, (e.g., LLaMA 2, Falcon or GPT-2), denoted as LLM. Additional input parameters include the beam size BBitalic\\_B, the number of candidate tokens sampled at each iteration from the LLM KKitalic\\_K, the LLM scaling factor α\\alphaitalic\\_α, and the token insertion bonus β\\betaitalic\\_β.\n\nThe algorithm maintains two main data structures. The beam at iteration nnitalic\\_n, denoted by ℬn\\mathcal{B}\\_{n}caligraphic\\_B start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT consists of a list of tuples, where each tuple contains the token sequence of a beam hypothesis, its corresponding alignment with the speech signal, and the associated score. The second structure is the candidate list 𝒞\\mathcal{C}caligraphic\\_C, which has a similar format: a list of tuples representing alternative hypotheses under consideration for the next decoding step.\n\nAt each iteration, we begin by clearing the candidate list (line 7). For each tuple in the beam from the previous iteration (line 8), we prompt the LLM with the current token sequence and sample KKitalic\\_K candidate tokens (line 9). For each candidate, we determine its start time using an alignment algorithm (line 11), compute the incremental score as defined in ([12](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S5.E12 \"In V Algorithmic Implementation ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\")) (line 12), and add the resulting tuple to the candidate list (line 13). The main loop terminates either when all beam hypotheses at iteration nnitalic\\_n have reached a stop criterion (see Section [VII](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S7 \"VII Experiments ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\")) or when a predefined safety horizon is reached. The final output is the hypothesis in the beam with the highest score. It is worth noting that identical beam prefixes are efficiently computed only once to avoid redundant processing.\n\nThe following functions are used in Algorithm [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#alg1 \"Algorithm 1 ‣ V Algorithmic Implementation ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\").\n\nLM.TopK(w1n−1,K)(w\\_{1}^{\\,n-1},K)( italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , italic\\_K ) returns the KKitalic\\_K most probable next tokens and their probabilities under the LLM, given a token sequence w1n−1w\\_{1}^{\\,n-1}italic\\_w start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.\n\nAM.AlignToken(w,a1n−1,𝐗)(w,a\\_{1}^{n-1},\\mathbf{X})( italic\\_w , italic\\_a start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_n - 1 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , bold\\_X ) uses Viterbi to find the best start time a^n\\hat{a}\\_{n}over^ start\\_ARG italic\\_a end\\_ARG start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_n end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT and returns the corresponding acoustic likelihood pAMp\\_{\\mathrm{AM}}italic\\_p start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman\\_AM end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT.\n\nBEAM.TopB(𝒞,B)(\\mathcal{C},B)( caligraphic\\_C , italic\\_B ) keeps the BBitalic\\_B highest-scoring hypotheses from 𝒞\\mathcal{C}caligraphic\\_C.\n\nBEAM.AllEOS checks whether every beam reached a stop criterion (see Section [VII](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S7 \"VII Experiments ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\") for details).\n\nBefore presenting the empirical evaluation, we note that the proposed approach has higher computational complexity compared to standard ASR inference using an N-gram model. Specifically, the computation of our method is of the order O​(T2​K​B)O(T^{2}KB)italic\\_O ( italic\\_T start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_K italic\\_B ), where TTitalic\\_T represents the number of audio frames in the input, KKitalic\\_K denotes the number of LLM token candidates, and BBitalic\\_B is the beam size.\n\n## VI Datasets\n\nOur system is evaluated on three widely recognized ASR datasets, leveraging pre-trained models that require no additional training or data collection. The evaluation datasets comprise the Wall Street Journal (WSJ0) test subset, TED-LIUM Release 3 test set, and a set of native American English speakers from the ALLSSTAR corpus [[40](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib40)].\n\nThe WSJ0 dataset comprises high-quality recordings of read speech from articles in the Wall Street Journal. It features 123 speakers and a balanced gender representation, making it a standard benchmark for structured speech recognition.\n\nThe TED-LIUM Release 3 test set consists of TED talk recordings that capture real-world, professional speech delivery in diverse scenarios. This combination of datasets enables us to comprehensively assess our system’s performance across various speaking styles while maintaining the original training configurations of the models.\n\nFrom the ALLSSTAR corpus [[40](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib40)], we select recordings of 26 native English speakers, comprising a total of 3,060 utterances, to establish a controlled evaluation baseline aimed at consistent speech patterns.\n\nOur method performs zero-shot inference. Therefore, it does not require a training set. For WSJ0 and TED-LIUM 3, we used the standard validation and test set. For ALLSSTAR, we used a separate set of 3 speakers, each with 100 utterances, for validation, ensuring no overlap with the test set, which consisted of 23 speakers with a total of 2,760 utterances.\n\n## VII Experiments\n\nOur experimental framework evaluates multiple acoustic and language models in a zero-shot setting, utilizing pre-trained models without any additional fine-tuning or adaptation. We utilized two state-of-the-art pre-trained acoustic models. The first is wav2vec 2.0 [[9](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib9)]. We evaluated two model sizes: Base (12 transformer encoder blocks with 95M parameters) and Large (24 blocks, 317M parameters). These models were pre-trained on a substantial amount of unsupervised data and subsequently fine-tuned on various supervised corpus sizes: 10 minutes, 100 hours, and 960 hours. The second acoustic model is HuBERT [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib10)], which comes in two model sizes: Large (24 encoder blocks, 300M parameters) and X-Large (48 encoder blocks, 1B parameters). All acoustic models were used in their off-the-shelf configurations.\n\nWe investigated three LLMs as language models: GPT-2 [[14](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib14)], Falcon [[41](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib41)], and LLaMA 2 [[15](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib15)]. Note that each LLM has a different set of tokens, all of which are BPE-based [[42](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib42)]. Hence, to match the different token sets to the acoustic models, we filtered each set to include only tokens comprising English alphabetic characters, excluding numeric and special characters, to ensure compatibility with the acoustic model character set.\n\nThe pre-processing pipeline includes adding a 0.5-second silence period to each audio input, which extends the input context and empirically improves model generation stability. We then employed Silero Voice Activity Detector (VAD) version 5 [[43](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#bib.bib43)] to trim irrelevant silence periods, optimizing the input for transcription. The parameters of Silero VAD included a start extension of 0.2 seconds and no end extension.\n\nThe decoding process utilizes beam search with beam size b=5b=5italic\\_b = 5 and considers the top k=5,000k=5,000italic\\_k = 5 , 000 candidates from the LLM’s predictions. We will discuss how these parameters were empirically determined in Section [VII-D](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S7.SS4 \"VII-D Beam size and number of LLM candidates ‣ VII Experiments ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\"). The decoding process employs three distinct stopping criteria: (i) completion assessment, which evaluates the likelihood of a hypothesis to be a complete sentence against the probability of adding any another token; (ii) validation of acoustic probability threshold, which terminates paths where new token additions result in probabilities falling below a threshold of 0.3, excluding whitespace tokens; and (iii) audio length alignment, which stops decoding when the generated transcript aligns with the entire duration of the input audio. These criteria work together to ensure both transcription completeness and acoustic fidelity.\n\n| Dataset | LM | α\\alphaitalic\\_α | β\\betaitalic\\_β |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| WSJ0 | LLaMA 2 | 0.0650 | 0.0051 |\n| Falcon | 0.0949 | 0.0073 |\n| GPT-2 | 0.0626 | 0.0090 |\n| TED-LIUM 3 | LLaMA 2 | 0.0679 | 0.0028 |\n| Falcon | 0.0695 | 0.0015 |\n| GPT-2 | 0.0689 | 0.0061 |\n| ALLSSTAR Eng | LLaMA 2 | 0.0694 | 0.0331 |\n| Falcon | 0.1379 | 0.0161 |\n| GPT-2 | 0.0999 | 0.0449 |\n\nOur implementation employed text normalization to ensure consistent evaluation. All texts were converted to lowercase, retaining only English alphabet characters. When processing acronyms, we merged consecutive single letters separated by spaces into a unified representation. We ensured a fair comparison between our system and beam search outputs by converting all acronyms to a standardized lowercase merged format, while addressing format variations, such as the dots in WSJ0’s reference texts.\n\n### VII-A Hyperparameters\n\nThe hyperparameters α\\alphaitalic\\_α and β\\betaitalic\\_β were tuned on the validation set for each dataset and for each LLM. The values of α\\alphaitalic\\_α and β\\betaitalic\\_β are shown in Table [I](https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02228v1#S7.T1 \"TABLE I ‣ VII Experiments ‣ Guiding an Automatic Speech Recognition Decoder using Large Language Models\"). The values of these hyperparameters remain consistent across different acoustic models. The consistency stems from the shared CTC loss function used in training the acoustic models, which results in similar emission probability distributions. This architectural advantage enables maintaining the same scaling parameters across different acoustic models, while only requiring adjustments for different language models with distinct vocabulary distributions, output characteristics, and various datasets.\n\n|  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | | | ALLSSTAR Eng | | WSJ0 | | TED-LIUM 3 | |\n| Acoustic Model | Decoder Type | Language Model | WER ↓\\downarrow↓ | CER ↓\\downarrow↓ | WER ↓\\downarrow↓ | CER ↓\\downarrow↓ | WER ↓\\downarrow↓ | CER ↓\\downarrow↓ |\n| wav2vec 2.0 Base 10m | greedy | – | 57.03 | 18.93 | 58.15 | 16.67 | 60.72 | 20.97 |\n|  | beam | 4-gram | 23.61 | 11.86 | 24.81 | 9.28 | 29.72 | 14.19 |\n|  | beam | GCNN | 20.62 | 9.70 | 22.40 | 8.02 | 26.83 | 12.34 |\n|  | beam | Transformer | 18.49 | 11.41 | 17.01 | 7.49 | 23.04 | 12.80 |\n|  | LLM beam | Falcon | 44.55 | 16.05 | 27.43 | 8.12 | 48.08 | 17.31 |\n|  |  | GPT-2 | 21.75 | 9.52 | 26.93 | 8.77 | 33.49 | 13.81 |\n|  |  | LLaMA 2 | 29.52 | 11.60 | 32.57 | 9.64 | 41.39 | 15.53 |\n| wav2vec 2.0 Large 10m | greedy | – | 58.95 | 20.76 | 60.32 | 18.22 | 62.44 | 23.21 |\n|  | beam | 4-gram | 24.64 | 12.53 | 26.29 | 10.14 | 30.11 | 16.53 |\n|  | beam | GCNN | 20.91 | 10.02 | 22.51 | 8.44 | 27.14 | 12.53 |\n|  | beam | Transformer | 18.01 | 10.11 | 16.35 | 7.46 | 23.73 | 13.37 |\n|  | LLM beam | Falcon | 44.43 | 16.29 | 27.24 | 8.47 | 43.63 | 15.08 |\n|  |  | GPT-2 | 22.04 | 10.26 | 24.05 | 8.61 | 30.65 | 13.21 |\n|  |  | LLaMA 2 | 29.90 | 11.94 | 32.94 | 10.00 | 41.22 | 15.64 |\n| wav2vec 2.0 Base 100h | greedy | – | 11.71 | 4.50 | 13.39 | 3.16 | 18.31 | 6.80 |\n|  | beam | 4-gram | 8.21 | 4.04 | 9.95 | 2.70 | 13.68 | 6.60 |\n|  | beam | GCNN | 7.21 | 3.33 | 9.14 | 2.42 | 12.95 | 6.04 |\