re assessed to have a low risk of bias and low risk of applicability concerns, as shown in Table[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#Tab3) and illustrated in Figs.[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#Fig2) and [3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#Fig3). For studies identified to have a moderate or high risk of bias and applicability concerns, the greatest contributing factor was patient selection, followed by index test. This was possibly due to some studies having unclear patient selection criteria, and some studies having controlled test environments, which may bias the index tests. The QUADAS-2 assessment of the included studies showed predominantly low risk of bias and applicability concerns, supporting the reliability of findings on LLMs as transcription tools in medical domains (Figs.[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#Fig2) and [3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#Fig3)). However, some studies, such as Zick et al. [[9](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#CR9)], Blackley et al. [[21](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#CR21)], Hodgson et al. [[16](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#CR16)], and Kodish-Wachs et al. [[17](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#CR17)], had high risk of bias in patient selection and applicability concerns, which may limit generalizability. Unclear reference standards in studies like Bundy et al. [[23](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#CR23)] and Goss et al. [[20](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12220090#CR20)] suggest potential gaps in validation. While the overall low risk in flow and timing strengthens confidence in the results, variability in methodological rigor underscores the need for standardised evaluation for future studies to ensure consistent and reliable conclusions.\n\nTable 3Detailed risk of bias assessment for the various studies using QUADAS-2 toolStudyR